english:
  title: Postscript to Park Neul's Calligraphy
  author: Kim Il-son
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Years ago, when I served at the office that oversaw the collation of the Gangmok, Park Gyeong came to work there as a scribe. Through our long association, I came to know his character—a man of the stripe of Qian Fu, one of antiquity's hidden worthies. Though poor, Gyeong earned his rice through his brush, yet his ambition lay elsewhere. One day I visited his modest home and saw his son. What a boy—the kind worth teaching, worth nurturing. His countenance was luminous, his responses measured and composed, his bearing quiet yet principled. This was Neul. When he grasped the brush to write a single character, each stroke held the weight of a measure of grain, alive with spirit. I was amazed, and knew then that Gyeong would have an heir worthy of his name.

    Had this boy been born into a noble house, he would surely have risen to prominence. Had he been born in those lands where talent is prized, he would certainly have earned the esteem of scholars and elder sages, the favor of princes and lords. He would not languish in such hunger and cold. Yet alas—our laws constrain us, our customs do not honor talent. Thus the father and son remain in straitened circumstances.

    Until now, I had found no words to record their merit. But fortune has granted them the recognition of Magistrate Kang, who has even composed verse in their honor. This is a turning point for the Park family. The ancients held the glory of the written word above rank itself, for talent is rare and recognition rarer still. Yet when Magistrate Kang's words spread, Neul's name became weighty in the world, and Gyeong too found his dignity restored. To receive such recognition the father and son value more than official position itself. How many in this world have gained office yet left no deeds worth recording? By this measure, Heaven has not been unkind to them after all.

    When Magistrate Kang departed southward, I gave him a scroll of Neul's calligraphy as a parting gift. He received it with great reverence, yet would not keep it for himself—he chose instead to present it to his own father. Such is Magistrate Kang: a man of refined sensibilities who seeks to honor those he loves in every way.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Qian Fu (潛夫): A Han dynasty scholar known for his integrity and refusal to seek office under unworthy rulers; here used to describe a person of hidden talent and virtue.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Gangmok (綱目): Likely referring to Zhu Xi''s comprehensive historical chronicle 資治通鑑綱目, known as Gangmok in Korean scholarly circles.'
  - key: ''
    value: The phrase 'worth teaching' derives from the classical allusion 窺牛 (peering at an ox), suggesting the child shows the simple, natural virtue of someone worth cultivating.
